tation \\\"org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:$libraryVersion\\\"\\n    testImplementation 'org.assertj:assertj-core:3.22.0'\\n}\\n\\ngraalvmNative {\\n    agent {\\n        defaultMode = \\\"conditional\\\"\\n        modes {\\n            conditional {\\n                userCodeFilterPath = \\\"user-code-filter.json\\\"\\n            }\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777590177148}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:1.1.10.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-30T23-05-01-338817Z.log:674:[thinking] I'm thinking about whether a class can implement an annotation interface, and it seems allowed. However, implementing it manually requires the equals/hashCode methods, which leads me to consider how it tests the interface contract and the existing equality standards for annotations. I should explore the issue patterns since the goal is to enhance tests for metadata coverage. Existing tests rely on reflection, but I want to add functional usage to trigger native code. I'll compile carefully, considering new features like `@ArquillianResource` for lambda parameter annotations. This is functional and not already covered by reflection, which is great!\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:1.1.10.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-30T23-05-01-338817Z.log:678:[thinking] I’m looking at a syntax example where I'm using an annotation on a lambda parameter, specifically with the target set to PARAMETER. Yes, I can do this if I'm using explicit types or var. Invoking the callback reads well since it utilizes the annotation public API without relying on reflection. That's a great feature! I wonder if this aligns with Arquillian's intentions from 2015 and whether a formal parameter includes lambda in its considerations. It feels like a different logic flow, which is interesting!\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:1.1.10.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-30T23-05-01-338817Z.log:682:[tool-call] delta {\"path\":\"tests/src/org.jboss.arquillian.test/arquillian-test-api/1.1.10.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_arquillian_test/arquillian_test_api/Arquillian_test_apiTest.java\",\"edits\":[{\"oldText\":\"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\",\"newText\":\"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void lambdaCallbackParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        ResourceUrlFormatter formatter = (@ArquillianResource(URL.class) URL resourceUrl) -> resourceUrl.toExternalForm();\\n        URL resourceUrl = URI.create(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\").toURL();\\n\\n        assertThat(formatter.format(resourceUrl)).isEqualTo(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static final class ResourceConsumer {\\n\",\"newText\":\"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @FunctionalInterface\\n    private interface ResourceUrlFormatter {\\n        String format(URL resourceUrl);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static final class ResourceConsumer {\\n\"}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:1.1.10.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-30T23-05-01-338817Z.log:683:[tool-call] end id=call_pKeZA7QMvmEueEKuSudFCgMR|fc_0f185721c1b445330169f3dfc909788193bf067d68dbfb3ba7 name=edit args={\"path\": \"tests/src/org.jboss.arquillian.test/arquillian-test-api/1.1.10.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_arquillian_test/arquillian_test_api/Arquillian_test_apiTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\", \"newText\": \"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void lambdaCallbackParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        ResourceUrlFormatter formatter = (@ArquillianResource(URL.class) URL resourceUrl) -> resourceUrl.toExternalForm();\\n        URL resourceUrl = URI.create(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\").toURL();\\n\\n        assertThat(formatter.format(resourceUrl)).isEqualTo(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static final class ResourceConsumer {\\n\", \"newText\": \"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @FunctionalInterface\\n    private interface ResourceUrlFormatter {\\n        String format(URL resourceUrl);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static final class ResourceConsumer {\\n\"}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jboss.arquillian.test:arquillian-test-api:1.1.10.Final/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-30T23-05-01-338817Z.log:684:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating enum usage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether enum constants are functional features. They serve as fields and can represent a fixed Arquillian resource, but ArquillianResource seems designed for injection fields rather than enum constants. That makes me wonder if using enum constants for this purpose is a bit unnatural. I should probably consider how this aligns or diverges from the intended use of ArquillianResource. It's intriguing to ponder the implications involved!\\n\\n**Considering annotation implementation**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether a class can implement an annotation interface, and it seems allowed. However, implementing it manually requires the equals/hashCode methods, which leads me to consider how it tests the interface contract and the existing equality standards for annotations. I should explore the issue patterns since the goal is to enhance tests for metadata coverage. Existing tests rely on reflection, but I want to add functional usage to trigger native code. I'll compile carefully, considering new features like `@ArquillianResource` for lambda parameter annotations. This is functional and not already covered by reflection, which is great!\\n\\n**Exploring lambda annotations**\\n\\nI’m looking at a syntax example where I'm using an annotation on a lambda parameter, specifically with the target set to PARAMETER. Yes, I can do this if I'm using explicit types or var. Invoking the callback reads well since it utilizes the annotation public API without relying on reflection. That's a great feature! I wonder if this aligns with Arquillian's intentions from 2015 and whether a formal parameter includes lambda in its considerations. It feels like a different logic flow, which is interesting!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0f185721c1b445330169f3dfab99ac81938d7b675bda217fd9\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp89_JTRvRlTBd5RUPQAP-FmM3Ewxow5Sn9PH84f5E7xAPNdv_m1JY4gn46qpGrTR8fvDzura_uboGqkDYFDAJq7eM8u9T_7R8NneT9JTn0zkBjRZtLFKBAAC7Mjgfzd9NFiVOzRY6pN-QsLbxY7a5zl9HTrzNRaImCzVHMpS5ofoLG4O1tKB3aCpb7k3NA6P_A7ZnTojzH71rAGNHCUfSEgv2synkBTMXVgaxlzITiGsktZt0Z8uwnb9Z21Y05m1KN6hK_LzeUDfW8DidU5JwOeKOm37OUH0W6wm8g0xYxgzlBtvkkCYo7aONPrQWF1qDWQS2trfAyjQi3o1yXKfIiItp7IoZ8T2vwa1WXF9n3B2fVu2xdcokeEWjvJx0k5fRMyNGk1SaFE_C69WwcQfkdKLoWPrUP6pJlEaY1D9RpTzl00ZBENa-pg7ZNVmKSbzpX2_YseUpDer5V5h-UltQrkee1r4iazl_c0UFAPI8pftPqhaTIPHdpPX3WCudXm7draeJrbzLPdcj7zvgRbgDw_SSEAJUxdRHCiAS6Be8mSN3byvBT_qPG1MV92e3bBzV02R3IsSpN6SylT6Bnk3eOfyCkOcVrbPBgTK-dhEUZsiowcjEyViUyloEwbMzB7WnQI3mnltGbqXAS4bl-ouJ1Rs3JCngz6wGaNAzDtLuJXH5YYAwIu7n2MCdGjM2nVixdsUqT-oxzMF9EWk8NyXRvKE_HFtsjiiUPeV2cz42OOY3o0ALSbgmMlmU6kwxZddTJoYRCS7WIq_ZGqOLLc5SMfSgprMu_cKNCks_gHYcEH9PlZlW0YjpoPCXT8xV_nn8ORrEtZkViux_Rh2251d6Yn2LH1Qur3Sat1m3InO6L