WmBfY11YX7-lbWj35QvEsXaavZRrZbLGAeTDCgpBdCcBGMjlj2nEkGZy7VuCZ_gBkDyr3z-yl1Y9e-NXVBUc2sU5DNyl_0a2QSH37npdr_oz6F5v_uH-kLWZOYFNcNxaYqlbI7gWoyzk_9QfLnXDh5yAwoJ4858nrN_abMIDhfcAs7NVWa5gvo2rKj4JVorBcsIQbePnqDOyWEoyRAfwaQbhofPdhGu4zrxFRH08UeiDgHSJbQc67CYbu1h8oDXRiLTQe5TWo_krco7zKKKFCgPmucXTPEPEEvmG-wb3zAJU33XNjPfL64-6QSJTyzP4MjlncYoBZsUdIBaVQj1SjyRGbjMesPPv-WpnwOPsVCwdOy0qsR2VqOigaIXy-GcyvDit4Vlwx10IxgnQjB1jwp0YmbJpwvJXAS8SIJBuP2F7iTkLMO_RJBQ0vKmOsJwTdoHfCp_2fNBznVyG9jiE1bhUScbAJZ76Dl-8L9dD_b0-67I4wPV2p20tirmyieRWVQ7_ICbQTbqHVLACp0muidYg5Z2a2P6TN53s-ysa0O0sG86jCrKRWA7-Gn0uzmuBvb-C3aZpqMHiESYFPQnOlJTUWVKXDul8RJoF3iE90P4oAS8awRzgyNLb48BbjfI9hbsLJrXk3QUoT5qbpqTeRxaAc1GbrZDr3wCxwY4oTVzQFgWCJ7dDazT-VEsiQ-cpjbuvxRUzQ6xSzzVI7bmSY3x-JTIOMbU6LVQ7EAmkBCAGynOHdIIZ_Ca_yubKcfU_bmyonfgkZg==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating enum usage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether enum constants are functional features. They serve as fields and can represent a fixed Arquillian resource, but ArquillianResource seems designed for injection fields rather than enum constants. That makes me wonder if using enum constants for this purpose is a bit unnatural. I should probably consider how this aligns or diverges from the intended use of ArquillianResource. It's intriguing to ponder the implications involved!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering annotation implementation**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether a class can implement an annotation interface, and it seems allowed. However, implementing it manually requires the equals/hashCode methods, which leads me to consider how it tests the interface contract and the existing equality standards for annotations. I should explore the issue patterns since the goal is to enhance tests for metadata coverage. Existing tests rely on reflection, but I want to add functional usage to trigger native code. I'll compile carefully, considering new features like `@ArquillianResource` for lambda parameter annotations. This is functional and not already covered by reflection, which is great!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring lambda annotations**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking at a syntax example where I'm using an annotation on a lambda parameter, specifically with the target set to PARAMETER. Yes, I can do this if I'm using explicit types or var. Invoking the callback reads well since it utilizes the annotation public API without relying on reflection. That's a great feature! I wonder if this aligns with Arquillian's intentions from 2015 and whether a formal parameter includes lambda in its considerations. It feels like a different logic flow, which is interesting!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_pKeZA7QMvmEueEKuSudFCgMR|fc_0f185721c1b445330169f3dfc909788193bf067d68dbfb3ba7\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.jboss.arquillian.test/arquillian-test-api/1.1.10.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_arquillian_test/arquillian_test_api/Arquillian_test_apiTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\", \"newText\": \"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(urlResource.value()).isEqualTo(URL.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void lambdaCallbackParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        ResourceUrlFormatter formatter = (@ArquillianResource(URL.class) URL resourceUrl) -> resourceUrl.toExternalForm();\\n        URL resourceUrl = URI.create(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\").toURL();\\n\\n        assertThat(formatter.format(resourceUrl)).isEqualTo(\\\"https://arquillian.example/deployments/app\\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void annotationContractAllowsRuntimeLookupOnFieldsAndParametersOnly() {\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static final class ResourceConsumer {\\n\", \"newText\": \"    private static ArquillianResource annotationOnField(String fieldName) throws Exception {\\n        Field field = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredField(fieldName);\\n        return field.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @FunctionalInterface\\n 