Existing tests rely on reflection, but I want to add functional usage to trigger native code. I'll compile carefully, considering new features like `@ArquillianResource` for lambda parameter annotations. This is functional and not already covered by reflection, which is great!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring lambda annotations**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking at a syntax example where I'm using an annotation on a lambda parameter, specifically with the target set to PARAMETER. Yes, I can do this if I'm using explicit types or var. Invoking the callback reads well since it utilizes the annotation public API without relying on reflection. That's a great feature! I wonder if this aligns with Arquillian's intentions from 2015 and whether a formal parameter includes lambda in its considerations. It feels like a different logic flow, which is interesting!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_pKeZA7QMvmEueEKuSudFCgMR|fc_0f185721c1b445330169f3dfc909788193bf067d68dbfb3ba7\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.jboss.arquillian.test/arquillian-test-api/1.1.10.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_arquillian_test/arquillian_test_api/Arquillian_test_apiTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void constructorParametersCanDeclareArquillianResources() throws Exception {\\n        Constructor<ResourceConsumer> constructor = ResourceConsumer.class.getDeclaredConstructor(Object.class, URL.class);\\n        Parameter defaultParameter = constructor.getParameters()[0];\\n        Parameter urlParameter = constructor.getParameters()[1];\\n\\n        ArquillianResource defaultResource = defaultParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        ArquillianResource urlResource = urlParameter.getAnnotation(ArquillianResource.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(defaultResource).isNotNull();\\n        assertThat(defaultResource.value()).isEqualTo(ArquillianResource.class);\\n        assertThat(urlResource).isNotNul